	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Moving forward improvements in the functioning of the EU dairy supply chain</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 October 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Following the 2010 EU milk package, the focus at both the EU and national level is on improving contractual arrangements between milk farmers and dairies, so as to promote transparency and a reduction in the gap between the prices paid farmers for their milk and the retail value of the milk.</p><p>In the UK, it is considered that ‘there is still significant scope for improving the contractual terms’ for dairy farmers, with the Co-op retail group being ‘the latest retailer to come to the market with a proposed contract for dedicated liquid supply, which pays a premium for complying with key conditions’. In the context of these retailer initiatives, farmers’ unions in the UK are seeking to ensure that ‘every farmer in Great Britain has access to a milk contract with certainty that their farmgate milk price will be calculated in a fair, equitable and transparent manner’.</p><p>Progress at the level of relations with retailers may not be disconnected from a recent vote in the European Parliament on the introduction of ‘compulsory contracts with price determination’. The European farmers’ organisation, Copa-Cogeca, has highlighted how ‘input prices have risen sharply by 19.8% since 2005 whilst market prices have climbed by only 7.8%’. This has given rise to calls for the EU Presidency to expedite the adoption of the EU milk package.</p><p>The European Milk Board for its part was critical of the price formula agreed, describing proposals as ‘a free ticket to put pressure on prices for the producers that have a weak position on the market’.</p><p>The UK House of Commons, Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee, meanwhile, has posted a report on the future of the UK dairy sector in the light of pending EU reforms. It calls on the UK government to ‘ensure that UK dairy farmers are offered written contracts by processors that specify either the raw milk price or the principles underpinning the price, the volume and timing of deliveries, as well as duration of the agreement’. These types of contracts are thought necessary to ensure a sound foundation for investment by both milk producers and milk processors.</p><p>The members of the UK parliament take the view that ‘Unless such contracts are made compulsory … there will be no improvement in the system that currently means our dairy farmers have little certainty over the price they will receive for their milk’. It is maintained that ‘without Government action, many more UK dairy producers will simply go to the wall’.</p><p>The UK Parliamentary Committee welcomed EC proposals ‘to make it considerably easier for dairy farmers to collaborate over prices and so increase their bargaining power’. More broadly the report argued that ‘the forthcoming abolition of EU milk quotas coupled with growing global demand for dairy products creates a significant window of opportunity for UK dairy production’. However in order to be able to capitalise on these opportunities, it is seen as essential that the issue of the ‘imbalance of bargaining power between dairy farmers and buyers’ be addressed. It was argued that ‘retailers must recognise that the current distribution of margins along the supply chain is unsustainable’, with a need arising for the establishment of ‘dedicated supply chains for processed dairy products’.</p><p>The Committee also called for greater support to research on developing value-added products in the dairy sector and greater technological innovation in both dairy production and processing. The Committee is broadly supportive of the EC milk package, but maintains that it will be ‘insufficient on its own to redress the problems in the UK industry’.</p>
		
		
