				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Current initiatives to strengthen the functioning of dairy supply chains have two main objectives: first, to prevent price instability on global markets from undermining the basis for milk production within the EU; second, to equip milk producers and dairy companies to respond to emerging opportunities on global markets.</p><p>The EU’s expanding safety-net policy represents the principal policy mechanisms for preventing price instability from undermining the basis for milk production. However, it is recognised that this could put excessive pressures on the EU budget if the functioning of dairy supply chains is not strengthened. Efforts are therefore under way to build new types of relationships between EU milk suppliers and European dairy companies, to insulate EU milk producers from the worst effects of price instability and better equip the EU dairy sector as whole to exploit emerging global market opportunities.</p><p>This experience is relevant to the ACP in two ways. First, the implementation of EU safety-net policies can generate stocks that subsequently need to be disposed of on world markets. Surges in EU exports of milk powder can then impact on the functioning of supply relationships between milk producers and dairy processors in ACP countries, as the balance of fresh milk and milk powder in processed products is modified to take advantage of the availability of cheaper milk powders. In this context, given the EU’s commitment to policy coherence, steps then need to be taken to ensure that this external dimension of EU safety-net policies in the dairy sector does not disrupt established and emerging supply relationships within ACP dairy sectors.</p><p>In addition, current EU policy initiatives on the functioning of dairy supply chains highlight the need for proactive government policies in promoting the balanced development of commercial relationships between milk producers and dairy processors, if sustainable dairy sector development is to be promoted in an era of heightened price volatility. This is something which ACP governments will need to explore, drawing on past experiences of promoting intra-sector dialogues behind national dairy sector development strategies.</p>
		</div>
		
